message.content:
We must find all transactions that add a liability under “Account Payable” (that is, purchases made on credit) and then compute the balance‐sheet total on the “end” date. (Note that the “Initial” transactions do not include any accounts payable.) 

Looking at the data, only purchase transactions with “payment_method” marked as “Account Payable” (and with an “Unpaid” status) will affect the liability “Accounts Payable.” In the table below these are the only rows that matter:

1. Transaction with id “Purchase20231231002”  
  • Amount = 1,000,000.00  
  • Payment method “Account Payable” and status “Unpaid.”

2. Transaction with id “Purchase20231231008”  
  • Amount = 1,000,000.00  
  • Payment method “Account Payable” (Unpaid).

3. Transaction with id “Purchase20231231012”  
  • Amount = 1,600,000.00  
  • Payment method “Account Payable” (Unpaid).

4. Transaction with id “Purchase20231231018”  
  • Amount = 3,000,000.00  
  • Payment method “Account Payable” (Unpaid).

None of the “Initial” transactions mention accounts payable (they are only for cash deposit, bank deposit, fixed assets, etc.) so the beginning balance for Accounts Payable is zero.

Now add up the amounts of the “Account Payable” purchases:  
  1,000,000.00 + 1,000,000.00 = 2,000,000.00  
  2,000,000.00 + 1,600,000.00 = 3,600,000.00  
  3,600,000.00 + 3,000,000.00 = 6,600,000.00

Thus, the initial Accounts Payable balance is 0.00 and the ending balance (after processing all transactions) is 6,600,000.00.

The answer in the required JSON format is:

{"solution": {"Accounts Payable Initial Value": "0.00", "Accounts Payable End Value": "6600000.00"} }
